3/5/2018

API

  • APIs (application programming interfaces) provide a standardized way for computer programs to talk to each other
  • Our interest is in using APIs associated with websites to scrape data.
    • For complex data or large database, APIs can be dramatically easier than other approaches
    • They are in some sense the approved way to scrape data from a website
    • They often require obtaining an api key that the website uses to regulate access
    • The website returns structured data such as XML, which must still be parsed
  • If you are really fortunate, there is an R package that has already taken care of most of the work

An example

Lets take a look at the geocode() function in the ggmap package

library(ggmap)
(hill.location <- geocode("Hill Center, Piscataway, NJ"))
##        lon      lat
## 1 -74.4627 40.52209

Be sure to paste http://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=110%20Frelinghuysen%20Road,%20Piscataway,%20NJ&sensor=false into a browser to see what the Google API returns; the geocode() function extracts just a piece of that.

print(ggmap(get_map(location = hill.location, zoom = 16)))

  • APIs vary a great deal in logical structure and the quality of documentation
    • A nice example is the documentation for the Google geocode API
  • If there is not already an R package (some can be found at https://cran.r-project.org/web/views/WebTechnologies.html), (a great deal of) programming is still required
  • The basic tools in R can be found in the httr and jsonlite packages

Back to movies

There is an exceptionally nice API documentation page for the Open Movie Database at http://www.omdbapi.com

  • Two issues should be immediately clear:
    • You can construct the API call using R (for example, using paste0), although it might be messy
    • The result might be structured, but its still complicated
  • The site https://zapier.com/learn/apis/chapter-3-data-formats/ can be very useful in understanding the structure of JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) and XML (eXtensible Markup Language).

An example

(You can get your own free api key at http://www.omdbapi.com/apikey.aspx )

library(httr)
library(curl)
library(jsonlite)
url <- paste0(
  "http://www.omdbapi.com/?apikey=", 
  api.key.omdb, "&t=The+Third+Man&y=&plot=short&r=json?"
)
json_result <- url %>% curl() %>% readLines()

JSON

HTML is used to shape the display of information, while XML and JSON are flexible formats designed to store data.

JSON is a similar, but more compact, format to XML (which well discuss next class)its been described as fat-free alternative to XMLand appears to be rapidly replacing it. There is an example at http://www.r-datacollection.com/materials/ch-3-xml/indy.json . Notice the key-value pairs.

And here is an example from the Wikipedia page for JSON

person_ex <- '
{
  "firstName": "John",
  "lastName": "Smith",
  "isAlive": true,
  "age": 25,
  "address": {
    "streetAddress": "21 2nd Street",
    "city": "New York",
    "state": "NY",
    "postalCode": "10021-3100"
  },
  "phoneNumbers": [
    {
      "type": "home",
      "number": "212 555-1234"
    },
    {
      "type": "office",
      "number": "646 555-4567"
    },
    {
      "type": "mobile",
      "number": "123 456-7890"
    }
  ],
  "children": [],
  "spouse": null
}
'

Notice that

  • the data is constructed as attributevalue pairs
  • address and phoneNumbers are nested entries
  • both [] and null are used for missing data
  • the data is both human-readable yet structured

If you find yourself using R in a web development setting, you may find yourself writing JSON files as well as reading them. The paper by Jeroen Ooms, co-author of the jsonlite package, is a good starting point.

fromJSON()

The fromJSON() function from the jsonlite does almost all of the work of bringing JSON-formatted data into R, but its worth paying attention to the options (which you can examine in detail with ?fromJSON).

library(jsonlite)
example_primatives <- '
[
  "Cook", 
  "Douglass", 
  "College Ave", 
  "Busch", 
  "Livingston"
]
'

fromJSON(example_primatives, simplifyVector = TRUE)
## [1] "Cook"        "Douglass"    "College Ave" "Busch"       "Livingston"
# simplifyVector = TRUE is the default
class(fromJSON(example_primatives))
## [1] "character"

Back to APIs

Earlier, we saw that the API call from http://www.omdbapi.com, given the title, had the form

http://www.omdbapi.com/??apikey=[YOUR_KEY_HERE]&t=The+Third+Man&y=&plot=short&r=json

and that we could get a named list with code like

library(httr)
library(curl)
library(jsonlite)
url <- paste0(
  "http://www.omdbapi.com/?apikey=", 
  api.key.omdb, 
  "&t=The+Third+Man&y=&plot=short&r=json?"
)
json_result <- url %>% fromJSON() %>% as.data.frame()

Suppose we wanted to write an R function to get the principal actors of a given movie. We could do it by

  1. Forming the proper API call for the movie
  2. Retrieving the results and parsing them
  3. Pulling out the piece we need

For the first step, there is a useful base R function URLencode() that will turn “The Third Man” into “The%20Third%20Man”. There is an even more useful function getForm() in the RCurl package, in which the first argument is the URL and the rest are name-value pairs:

getForm(
  uri = "http://www.omdbapi.com/", 
  apikey = api.key.omdb,
  t = "The Third Man"
)

Putting this together, we might first have the series of steps

omdb_result <- getForm(uri = "http://www.omdbapi.com/", 
                       apikey = api.key.omdb,
                       t = "The Third Man")
json_result <- omdb_result %>% fromJSON() 
actors <- str_trim(str_split(json_result$Actors, ",")[[1]])
actors
## [1] "Joseph Cotten" "Alida Valli"   "Orson Welles"  "Trevor Howard"

This might lead to the following function

omdb_title_actors <- function(title){
    library(RCurl)
    library(stringr)
    if (length(title) > 1) stop("Only one movie title at a time")
    omdb_result <- getForm(
      uri = "http://www.omdbapi.com/", 
      apikey = api.key.omdb, 
      t = title
    )
    actors <- omdb_result %>% 
      fromJSON() %>% 
      .[["Actors"]]
    str_trim(str_split(actors, ",")[[1]])
}

omdb_title_actors("All about Eve")
## [1] "Bette Davis"    "Anne Baxter"    "George Sanders" "Celeste Holm"
omdb_title_actors("The Lady Eve")
## [1] "Barbara Stanwyck" "Henry Fonda"      "Charles Coburn"  
## [4] "Eugene Pallette"

Using an API key

  • Most sites with APIs require the use of an API key. There will be some sort of registration process, sometimes with paid options. See for example, https://www.wunderground.com/weather/api/d/pricing.html (which is automatic, with paid options) and https://omim.org/api (which requires human review)
  • API keys are not unlike passwordsyou dont want to put them in your source files, unless you are sure youll never share those source files.
    • There is a description of various approaches to hiding them at http://blog.revolutionanalytics.com/2015/11/how-to-store-and-use-authentication-details-with-r.html
    • I have no keys that require tight security, so I just have a separate file with the key that I read in

OAuth

  • There is another authentication method known as OAuth, which you can read up on your own; the httr package documentation has multiple examples

An example with an API key

  • The Wunderground API for, say a 10-day forecast, looks like
http://api.wunderground.com/api/Your_Key/forecast10day/
  q/CA/San_Francisco.json

and returns JSON.

  • Lets first build up a reasonable result
wunderground_base_url <- paste0("http://api.wunderground.com/api/",
  api.key.wunderground) 
wunderground_full_url <- paste0(
  wunderground_base_url, 
  "/forecast10day/q/NJ/", 
  URLencode("New Brunswick"), 
  ".json"
)

wunderground_get <- wunderground_full_url %>% 
  GET() 
http_status(wunderground_get)
## $category
## [1] "Success"
## 
## $reason
## [1] "OK"
## 
## $message
## [1] "Success: (200) OK"
wunderground_results <- wunderground_get %>% 
  content(as = "text") %>% 
  fromJSON()
# I've used GET() followed by content() from the httr package instead of curl() and readLines() from the curl package

Or, if we dont care about the http status, we could use the higher level code for a simpler version

wunderground_results <-  wunderground_full_url %>% 
  fromJSON()

Putting it all into a function

get_wunderground_forecast <- function(city, state, api.key = api.key.wunderground){
  # get 10 day forecast using Wunderground's API
  if (nchar(state) != 2) stop("Please use 2-letter state abbreviation")
  library(httr)
  library(jsonlite)
  base_url <- paste0("http://api.wunderground.com/api/", api.key.wunderground) 
  full_url <- paste0(base_url, 
        "/forecast10day/q/", state, "/", URLencode(city), ".json")
  wunderground_get <- full_url %>% GET() 
  if (http_status(wunderground_get)$category != "Success") stop(paste("Couldn't retrieve the page:", http_status(wunderground_results)$get))
  wunderground_df <- wunderground_get %>% content(as = "text") %>% fromJSON() %>% 
      .[["forecast"]] %>% .[["simpleforecast"]] %>% .[["forecastday"]]
  with(wunderground_df, 
    data.frame(stringsAsFactors = FALSE, 
      date = date$pretty,
      date.year = date$year,
      date.month = date$month,
      date.day = date$day,
      weekday = date$weekday_short,
      period,
      high = high$fahrenheit,
      low = low$fahrenheit,
      conditions,
      pop))
}

It works!

Notice the use of the http_status() function in the httr package to check that the page was retrieved correctly. The function gives both codes and text, but you can also find the codes at https://http.cat

There are many wrappers for APIs, but even more APIs, out there. Some sources:

  • http://ropensci.org/
  • https://github.com/ropensci/opendata
  • https://cran.r-project.org/web/views/WebTechnologies.html

In class exercise

Look at the API documentation at https://dev.socrata.com/foundry/healthdata.nj.gov/9hse-wixk

Write a function that will use the API and then generate a plot of the rate of heart disease over time by year. Set the default to all races, but include an option to specify the race. To get ggplot2 to generate a plot from within a function, wrap the final object in the print() function.
